I'll solve this step by step, calculating each financial ratio based on the provided financial statements.

## Operating Cash Flow Ratio
This measures the company's ability to cover current liabilities with operating cash flows.
= Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities
= -967,147.02 / 7,605,149.91
= -0.127 (rounded to 3 decimal places)

## Cash Flow to Debt Ratio
This measures the company's ability to repay its debt using operating cash flow.
= Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities
= -967,147.02 / 7,605,149.91
= -0.127 (rounded to 3 decimal places)

## Inventory Turnover Ratio
This measures how many times a company sells and replaces its inventory during a period.
= Cost of Goods Sold / Average Inventory
= 496,220.00 / ((0 + 8,466,430.00) / 2)
= 496,220.00 / 4,233,215.00
= 0.117 (rounded to 3 decimal places)

## Debt to Equity Ratio
This measures the proportion of debt to equity used to finance the company's assets.
= Total Current Liabilities / Total Owner's Equity
= 7,605,149.91 / 16,112,375.10
= 0.472 (rounded to 3 decimal places)

## Quick Ratio
This measures the company's ability to cover short-term liabilities with quick assets.
= (Total Current Assets - Inventory) / Total Current Liabilities
= (14,619,619.72 - 8,466,430.00) / 7,605,149.91
= 6,153,189.72 / 7,605,149.91
= 0.809 (rounded to 3 decimal places)

## Current Ratio
This measures the company's ability to pay short-term liabilities with short-term assets.
= Total Current Assets / Total Current Liabilities
= 14,619,619.72 / 7,605,149.91
= 1.922 (rounded to 3 decimal places)
